# Command helm

## What does this command do:

The Kubernetes Package Manager

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: sudo dnf install helm
For Raspberry Pi install using: curl -fsSL https://packages.buildkite.com/helm-linux/helm-debian/gpgkey | gpg --dearmor | sudo tee /usr/share/keyrings/helm.gpg > /dev/null && echo "deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/helm.gpg] https://packages.buildkite.com/helm-linux/helm-debian/any/ any main" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/helm-stable-debian.list && sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get install helm
For Mac install using: brew install helm

## Command path

For Fedora run: /usr/bin/helm
For Raspberry Pi run: /usr/bin/helm
For Mac run: /opt/homebrew/bin/helm

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/helm/helm

## Command options

# Search for a chart in configured repos
helm search repo <keyword>

# Search Artifact Hub for charts
helm search hub <keyword>

# Add a chart repository
helm repo add <name> <url>

# List configured repositories
helm repo list

# Update repository indexes
helm repo update

# Install a chart as a new release
helm install <release-name> <chart>

# Install with custom values
helm install <release-name> <chart> -f values.yaml
helm install <release-name> <chart> --set key=value

# Install into a specific namespace
helm install <release-name> <chart> -n <namespace> --create-namespace

# List all releases
helm list
helm list -n <namespace>
helm list -A   # all namespaces

# Upgrade an existing release
helm upgrade <release-name> <chart>
helm upgrade --install <release-name> <chart>   # install if not present

# Uninstall a release
helm uninstall <release-name> -n <namespace>

# Roll back a release to a previous revision
helm rollback <release-name> <revision>

# Show release history
helm history <release-name>

# Show release status
helm status <release-name>

# Show chart values/readme/chart metadata
helm show values <chart>
helm show readme <chart>
helm show chart <chart>

# Download a chart without installing
helm pull <chart> --untar

# Render templates locally (dry run)
helm template <release-name> <chart>
helm template <release-name> <chart> -f values.yaml

# Lint a chart for issues
helm lint <chart-dir>

# Create a new chart scaffold
helm create <chart-name>

# Package a chart directory into a .tgz archive
helm package <chart-dir>

# Show helm environment variables
helm env

# Print client version
helm version

# Generate shell autocompletion
helm completion bash | sudo tee /etc/bash_completion.d/helm
helm completion zsh > ~/.zsh/completions/_helm
